{"/service/ndnp/txdn/batch_txdn_evans_ver01/data/sn86063730/00332894195/1930022101/0379.xml":{"full_text":"I\nShe tSnmmsuffle fkralO\nEstablished July 4, 1892\nEntered as second-class matter In the Postoffice\nBrownsville. Texas.\nTHE BROWNSVILLE HERALD PUBLISHING\nCOMPANY\nSubscription Rates\u2014Daily and Sunday (7 Isaacs)\nOne Year ...$9 00\nBlx Months ..$4.50\nThree Months. ,....$2.25\nDne Month.. .75\nMEMBER OF THE ASSOCIATED PRESS\nThe Associated Press is exclusively entitled to the use\nfar publication of all news dispatches credited to it or\nnot otherwise credited In this paper, and also the\nlocal news published herein.\nHarlingen Office, Reese-Wil-Mond Hotel. Phone 1020.\nTEXAS DAILY PRESS LEAGUE\nNational Advertising Representatives\nDallas, Texas, 512 Mercantile Bank Building.\nKansas City. Mo., 306 Coca Cola Building.\nChicago. Ill- Association Building.\nNew York. 350 Madison Avenue.\n8t. Louis. 502 Star Building.\nLos Angeles. Cal.. Room 1015 New Orpheum Bldg..\n146 8. Broadway.\nSan Francisco. Cal.. 318 Kohl Building.\nMexico and Our Water Supply\nGood relations with Mexico are of extreme import\nance to the Valley just now.\nThe immediate reason is that a water treaty guar\nanteeing the Valley's supply is being negotiated.\nThe general Reason is. of course, that we want to\nlive on friendly relations with our neighbors.\nWhen the Valley is faced with this situation, con\ngressmen from our own state are doing everything\nthey can to pass legislation which will hurt us.\nAbout 60 per cent of the water which comes down\nthe Rio Grande in the Valley comes from streams In\nMexico. Mexico could take all this water before it\nreaches the Rio Grande, and nothing could be said.\nShe is now building dams to carry' out part of that\npossiDimy.\nThis might hurt the Valley under present condi\ntions.\nStill there is no reason for alarm on the water\nsituation, if friendly relations can be kept with Mexi\nco. so that storage dams can be built.\nWe are told by engineers that the annual flow\nof the Rio Grande is around 5.000.000 acre-feet. Less\nthan 1.000.000 acre-feet is now used in irrigation\nalong the river, and much of this is wasted in faulty\nIrrigation works.\nThere is plenty of water for all, If storage dams\nare built to conserve the water.\nNegotiations have been in progress for some time\nto reach a water treaty with Mexico so that such\ndams can be built.\nEverything that tends to disrupt friendly rela\ntions with Mexico hurts our chance for such a treaty.\nThe Box bill, the Johnson bill. Mexicans illeeally\ndeported\u2014all such unwise and unfriendly actions\nwill hurt the Valley in its chance to secure its water\nguarantees.\nWe claim the normal flow of the Rio Grande as\nours by right of prior beneficial use. If our govern\nment follows a reasonable course. It seems certain\nthese rights will be guaranteed to us.\nBut we should remember, and should impress the\nfact on our congressmen from North Texas, that\nMexico has the power to take the water, since it\noriginates in her country, and that she is fast pre\nparing to do so.\nDisarming the Mexican Pistol\nToters\nPresident Pascual Rubio of Mexico has launched\nft campaign against the automatic. That is he has\nInstructed the police authorities of the City of Mexico\nto confiscate the pistols of all persons who are without\npermit. It is a very drastic order. Rubio plans to\ntake pistols away from the entire civilian popula\ntion of the republic. After he has recovered suf\nficiently to direct the work personally he intends to\nwithdraw- all pistol permits. It is another noble ex\nperiment. Rubio is an engineer. There Is an engi\nneer president of the United States. He is wTcst\u2019.lng\nwith a noble experiment and all its perplexing ln\ntracacies.\nMORE NEWS FROM THE WINTER RESORTS\n(Copyright, 1930, by The Associated Newspapers.)\nSt. Augustine, Fla.\u2014Mr. and Mrs. Winfield Zilch\nhave arrived here by automobile from their home in\nDayton, Ohio. The unhappy couple make the trip\nby car every season if it kills them. This year Mr.\nZilch looked particularly weakened by back-seat driv\ning. \u201cI'll tie all right again by the time we're ready\nto start back,\" he sighed wearily from his hotel bed\ntoday.\nMr. and Mrs Gregory Dilldoch and their police\ndog Napoleon also tooled into town by auto this\nmorning, looking much the worse for wear after a\n1,400-mile drive from Springfield, Mass. The dog\nstood it as long as it could but turned on Mr. Dill\ndoch and bit him passing through Brunswick, Geor\ngia. Mr. Dilldoch stood it as far as Jacksonville\nwhere he bit both the dog and Mrs. Dilldoch.\nColonel and Mrs. Jeptha Willetts, who come here\nyear after year without having much of an idea how\nto enjoy themselves, are spending their usual two\nweeks arguing with hackmen and storekeepers over\nrates.\nThe croquet players are at it in the public square\nand the enmities incurred have exceeded the 1929 fig\nures by 20 per cent, so far, with the season still\nyoung.\nThe guides outside the old Spanish fort on the\nwaterfront are pretty disgusted. Two Northern\nschoolgirls walked up to them this week and asked\nif it was off here that the Maine was sunk.\nORMOND\nGathering at the first tee every morning at 10\no\u2019clock to see the world\u2019.\", most famous golfer drive off\nis still the chief outdoor sport here. No, not Bobby\nJones; John D. Rockefeller.\nMr. Rockefeller plays eight holes a day. He Is 90\nyears old and that Is also his average score.\nMr. and Mrs. Wesley Prunedish. who are spending\na few days here, will wait one day more. If the oil\nking doesn\u2019t give them new dime they will de\nnounce him and leave.\nMotoring up and down the beach between here\nand Daytona Beach continues to be the favorite\nrecreation of thousands of visitors whose Ideas of\ndiversion are hard to understand.\nDAYTONA BEACH\nMr. and Mrs. Emory D. L. Whipsay are both con\nfined to their beds under the care of doctors. They\nanswered one of those newspaper advertisements\nreadme. \u2018Lady and gentleman motoring South in\nfive-passenger car can accommodate another con\ngenial couple.\u201d The gentleman turned out to be an\nunreformed dirt-track automobile racer. The lady,\naccording to Mrs. Whipsaw, was no lady.\nMr. and Mrs. Casper Mulllgitawney of Penobscot.\nMaine, who came here by flivver, are very indignant\nbecause, although there are three or four free\nbridges across the Halifax river they had to choose\nthe one toll-bridge.\nMr. and Mrs. Luke Cupcake and their daughter,\nAbbie. who arrived here with a new camera Thursday,\nhave used up their tenth film taking pictures of one\nanother in front of the swell hotels, although they are\nputting up at a boarding-house.\nMajor T. Haithwalte Palooka. who came here by\nauto, is waxing quite Indignant because he was held\nup by police put on the roads in the Florida fruit\nfly quarantine. \u201cDo I look like a fruit-flv?\u201d he\ndemands. People are slow In answering him.\nCan you fancy the broodings In after life of a girl\nchosen Miss Universe and who later loses her looks\nand becomes just plain Mrs. Addison Gimlet or some\nthing like that?\nThe rediscount rate has dropped to 4 per cent, and\nIma Dodo says she doesn't care as she sold hers at\n4>i.\n_\nTHE OLD HOME TOWN.Stanley\nI\n_____ l\nI\nCHAPTER 50\nIt was, perhaps, fifteen minutes\nlater that Captain Lee entered the\ncabin and took his seat at the din\ning table. The deck hand had of\nfered no resistance whatever, he\nsaid, not even asking the reason\nfor locking him up.\n\"He knows the reason well\nenough!\" declared Margery, her\nblue eyes flashing at the recollec\ntion of the fellow's deed. \"He knew\nI had recognized him when he saw\nme. That\u2019s why he turned and ran!\nHe has been very careful since we\nleft New York to keep out of my\nsight. It was just by a lucky chance\n\u2014for us\u2014that I saw him tonight!\"\nThe incident was the sole topic,\nalmost, throughout the dinner. Ev\nery conceivable conjecture was ad\nvanced as to what form of deviltry\nexecution of the fellow\u2019s plan would\nhave taken. That Jimmy was to\nhave been the victim none doubted.\nIt was the general belief, also, that\nthe purnose had been murder.\nAs Pat and her guests were about\nto rise lrom the table. Captain Lee\nturned to the yacht\u2019s new owner,\na look of concern on his weather\nbeaten face\n\"It would be the part of wisdom,\nMiss Blair,\u201d he said in his slow,\ncareful way of speaking, \u201cso long\nas you aren\u2019t in any particular hur\nry. for us to drop anchor somewhere\nalong here and wait for daylight\nbefore we proceed. As I've told you,\nthere are many hidden coral reefs\nin these waters and we might slam\nonto one, even though there is a\nfull moon. What do you think about\nIt? Shall we keep on running oi\ndrop the hook?\u201d\n\u201cOh. if there is any danger. Cap\ntain, I\u2019d say to anchor, by all\nmeans!\u201d replied Pat. She looked In\nquiringly at the others. \"Don\u2019t you\nall agree?\" she queried.\nThe question received a general\naffirmative answer. Ten minutes\nlater the Bluebird came to a stop\nsome two miles off the east shore\nof Barbados, where anchorage was\nfound.\nThe warm, perfumed air of the\ntropical night drew everyone to the\nvessel's after deck to which, easy\nchairs had been brought up by the\nwaiters from the cabin. The big\nsouthern moon, double In size,\nseemingly, to the moon of the\nnorth, was just riding out of the\nocean in the east.\n\"Glorious, wonderful!\" breathed\nPat. a little quiver of rapture in the\nsweet contralto tones as she lay\nback in her chair, her eyes uplifted\nand shining in the sky's reflected\nsplendor. Two men sitting close by\nand facing her, one on each side,\nj Grab Bag\n!_I\nreui u\u00bbry -i. i\u00bbou\nWho am I? What state do I rep\nresent in the senate? Whom did I\nsucceed?\nWho is the president general of\nthe Daughters of the American\nRevolution?\nWhat is the capital of Jamaica?\n\u201cAnd whosoever shall offend one\nof these little ones that believe in\nme. it is better for him that a mill\nstone were hanged about his neck,\nand he were cast into the sea.\u201d\nWhere is this passage found in the\nBible?\nCorrectly Speaking\u2014\nRemember, constant usage of an\nexpression does not make it good\nEnglish. Think of this the next time\nyou say \"hadn\u2019t ought\u201d or \u201che dont.\u201d\nToday\u2019s Anniversary\nOn this date, in 1885, the Wash\nington monument was dedicated in\nthe District of Columbia.\nToday's Horoscope\nPersons bom on this day are very\nreliable. They can be trusted to\nwork without supervision.\nAnswers to Foregoing Questions\n1. Roscoe C. McCulloch; Ohio;\nTheodore E. Burton.\n2. Mrs. Lowell F. Hobart.\n3. Kingston.\n4. St. Mark, ix. 42.\nStar Lore\nTHE BIRTH OF A STAR\nBy Arthur DeV. Carpenter\nIt would be wonderful to be able\nto trace the actual beginning of a\nstar. The astronomer and scientist\ncan quite effectively go back in his\nintelligent imagination and behold\nthe time when there was a very thin\ngas distributed through space. This\ninfinitely vast cloud doubtless broke\nup and formed galaxies of spiral\nnebulae, and finally each spiral\nnebulae condensed into stars. At\nfirst a star must have been of so\nthin a composition that to be com\npared with anything material of\nwhich we know, it would be the\nequivalent of a near vacuum. Then\nby process covering untold ages, it\ncondensed, and generated heat and\nlight.\nlooked into the dark eyes, humid\nin the light of the moon and they,\ntoo, murmured: \u201cGlorious, wonder\nfull\u201d But neither referred to the\nglory or the wonder of the sky.\nJimmy \u2018Blair occupied a deep\ncushioned chair nearby. In close\nproximity, so close she had but to\nmove her hand a few inches to rest\nit on his. sat Margery. Jimmy also\nlay with his head back gazing up\nInto the brilliantly lit heavens.\nLooking into his eyes the girl mar\nvelled at the inexplicable mystery\nthat lay behind them. Of what was\nhe thinking? For it was Inconceiv\nable that no thought of any de\nscription occupied that twisted\nbrain. He must be thinking of\nsomething. What was it?\nHad she possessed the power to\nproject the off-put of her own mind\ninto the midst of coming events\nand read there the underlying story\nthat destiny was then shaping, she\nwould have marvelled even more\nover the strange workings cf the\nhuman brain. Not possessing that\npower she confined her attention\nto matters at hand.\nThen someone suggested a song,\nwhereupon, Lucy's guitar was\nbrought up and the latest popular\nairs began to waft their melody\nacross the calm waters of the Car\nibbean. Rex had a good tenor voice\nand the doctor owned an uncom\nmonly good bass. These with Pat's\nrich contralto, and the sopranos of\nthe two other girls, produced a com-\nbination equal to many of the\nprofessional quintettes.\nIt was eleven o'clock and after\nbefore the deck party began to dis\nintegrate. First, the lawyer and his\nwife and Aunt Lottie retired to\ntheir staterooms. Then Dr. Gordon\nrose, stretched luxuriously and de\nclared himself \u201cabout ready to hit\nthe hay.\u201d But he must have chang\ned his mind almost immediately,\nfor instead of retiring to the cabin,\nhe strolled forward. A few minutes\nafterward Lucy and Margery, tak\ning Jimmy with them, started for\nthe galley with the avowed Inten\ntion of \u201ccopping a snack.\u201d Pat and\nRex were thus left to the seclusion\nof their own devices.\n\u201cDon't you feel the spell of this\nwonderful night, Rex?\" asked-the\ngirl, breaking a long silence that\nfollowed the departure of Jimmy\nand his escorts. \u201cI just love to sit\nhere and watch the stars glimmer\nand glow! And that marvelous\nmoon' Isn\u2019t it all just perfectly\ngrand?\u201d\nAs she put the query her gaze\nshifted from the heavenly bodies,\ndropping to the level of the man\u2019s\neyes in which lay revealed, all the\nunspoken love in his heart. In the\ndark eyes looking straight into his\nhe read something\u2014or thought he\ndid. at least\u2014that he had not dared\nhope ever to see there. A little cry\ngurgled from his lips and he caught\nher hand, lying in her lap, in both\nof his.\n\"Pat\u2014mv dear!\" rne name ana\nthe endearing term were not spoken.\nThev were gasped out with a trem\nbling huskiness. \"I\u2014I\u2014\u201d Some\nthing rose up in his throat, lie\nswallowed It with a mighty effort,\nand tried again. You know. dear,\nthat I\u2014I love you!\u201d Again he was\nforced to stop. It was the hardest\nwork that had ever been put upon\nRex Dallard in his entire life\nOnce more he swallowed the lump.\nThen: *T can\u2019t ex\u2014exnect. of course,\nthat\u2014that you care for me! That\nIs. as I care, but I do love you. Pat.\nvery dearly!\"\n\u2022Do you. Rex\u2014dear?\u201d came the\nsoftlv whispered acknowledgement.\nWhether it was meant for a con\nfession of love on her part or not.\nit must have sounded so to Rex\nant! strangely sweet, too\u2014if the\nswiftness of motion with which he\nleaned over, caught her two arms\nand pulled her forward on his lap\nin the inclosure of the deep chair\nwas any evidence. And from the\nmanner in which she accented and\n\u2014yes, returned\u2014his ardent ki\u00ab6 it\nmust have been a correct assump\ntion on Rex\u2019s part that he hadn\u2019t\nmade any grievous mistake. To\nmake doubly certain he began an\nother. _\nIt was this one that Dr. Gordon,\nhaving smoked an entire cigar in\nthe solitude of the yacht's port\nbow, where he had stood commun-1\ning with the spirit of the nieht.\nhappened to glimpse as he stepped\ninto the opening of the after-deck.\nThat the sieht was a Jolt to the\ndoctor\u2019s peace of mind, there can be\nbut little doubt. Judging by his ac\ntions. For. as his caze settled on\nthe couple In the big chair, the\nlight from the moon clearly out\nlining the two. the man\u2019s face bent\ndown over the girl\u2019s upturned to\nhis. Dr. Gordon stopped short. For\na second or two he stood there and\nthen turning, lurched rather than\nwalked, back to the place in the\nport how. where he had stood\ndreaming ft dream\u2014a futile impos\nsible dream, he now realized.\nAnd the two hark on the efter\ndeck sitting in the mellow light or\nhe Southern moon they were\nliving through the first fond rap\ntures of their love\u2019s drram And\nas they sat there under the stars\nhe told her again the old story\nand she listened and smiled just as\n__\u2014\u2014 __\nSAMBO\u2019S PHILOSOPHY\n\u201cSome folkses nevah thinks \u2019bout\nsavin\u2019 up fo* a rainy day \u2019til hit gits\nblack, an' begins to thundah.\u201d\n1\n\nwomen have listened and smiled j\ndown through the centuries.\nIt was one of the waiters coming\nup to carry the chairs back into the 1\ncabin that brought the couple out\nof their dream and sent Pat scur\nrying down to her stateroom. Rex\nfollowed shortly afterward to his\nown.\nRex and Jimmy occupied the last\napartment on the starboard side,\nadjoining the entrance into the\nlazarette. Jimmy had the lower and\nRex the upper berth.\nAfter reaching the seclusion of\nher stateroom. Pat stood for a few\nmoments looking out the window\non the moon-lit ocean.\n(TO BE CONTINUED)\nRio Hondo Climbing\nAs Shipping Center\n\u2022Special to The Herald.)\nRIO HONDO, Feb. 21\u2014Setting a\nnew record for daily average ship\nment of citrus and other agricul\ntural products of better than four\ncarloads, and reaching a new high\ntotal for the season of 150 carloads\nto date, Rio Hondo has climbed to\nseventh place in the Calley ship\nping.\nFigures to this effect were re\nleased this week by A. B. Waldron.\nex^utive general agent for the\nMissouri Pacific Railway.\nA year ago this town was in\nfourteenth place in regard to agri\ncultural produce movement. Rapid\ndevelopment and opening up of\nnew land to farming has made this\nnew record possible, it Is asserted.\nIncluded in the total of 150 cars\nare 141 vegetables and nine citrus.\nPFER S DAUGHTER AIR PILOT\nLONDON\u2014The daughter of Lord\nInchcape has passed the air pilot\ntests and bought an aeroplane for\nher personal use._\nU I II I HiWg\nATTENTION!?\nWe have added a\n2 Rental Library to our\nX store! Come in and look\nI it over. All of the best X:\nsellers of all publishers. I\nKeep abreast of the\nmost popular new books\nby renting them at\nsmall cost!\nj HARGROVE\u2019S\nI Stationery Book Store\nPhone 348\nBrownsville, Texas\nthe safe and proved remedy\na laxative quinine. It\ncleanses the system and the\nquinine relieves the cold.\nGrove's\ndruggvU\nLaxative\nBROMO\nQUININE\nTabletsJ.\nSuccessful Since 1889\nFEED GRAIN\nAND\nHAY\nMcLELLAND FEED CO.,\nPhone 765 508 N. Commerce\nHarlingen\nj Day In Congress j\n(By Associated Press.)\nFriday:\nSenate:\nContinues consideration of tariff\nbill.\nLobby committee continues Mus\ncle Shoals investigation.\nHouse:\nContinued consideration of first\ndeficiency bill under the five-min\nute rule.\nBanking committee holds hearing\non bill to provide federal examiners\nfor federal land and joint stock\nland ranks.\nThursday:\nSenate:\nCompleted consideration of agri\ncultural rates in tariff bill.\nConfirmed nomination of Hugh M.\nTate of Knoxville, Tennessee, as\nmember of interstate commerce\ncommission.\nHouse:\nCompleted general debate on first\ndeficiency bill.\nHeard protest by chairman White\nof Merchant Marine committee\nagainst \u2018\u2022unfair'* practices of Can\nada and the Cunard line against\nAmerican shipping interest*.\nJudiciary committee took addi\ntional testimony on proposals to re\npeal or amend eighteenth amend\nment.\nCHILD FINDS FAMILY DEAD\nDULUTH, Minn.\u2014Returning from\na party. 8-vear-old Florence Kilgore\nfound her parents and two bro\nthers asphyxiated.\nA. TAMM\nBlue Printing and\nSupplies\nHarlingen, Texas\n1911 1930\nSkelton Abstract Co.\nAbstracts of Title Title Insurance\nMerchants Bank Building Rrownsville\nDependable Phone 353 Prompt\nBROWNSVILLE TITLE COMPANY\nBROWNSVILLE, TEXAS\nAbstracts of Title Title Insurance\nH\u2019e cover all lands In Cameron County\nCARNEIRO, CHUMNEY COMPANY\nCertified Public Accountants\nIncome Tax Service\nBROWNSVILLE SAN ANTONIO CORPUS OHRISTI\nState National Ban! Smith-Young Tower Nixon Building\nPROSPERITY x\nm\nt\nProsperity for Brownsville and\nthe Valley is a tangible, able-to\nbe-seen condition. Citrus groves\nare beginning to bloom vege\ntables are commanding good\nprices generally the interna\ntional airport and the bright\nprospects for a deep water port\u2014\nall are encouraging a splendid I\nbusiness outlook for Brownsville\nand the Valley.\nLet us. as your bank, help\nyou with any problems you\nmay wish to discuss with us.\nFirst National fianlc\nEstablished in 1891\nBROWNSVILLE, TEXAS\nTITLE INSURANCE\nWhen you borrow money on real estate, many loan companies re\nquire the title to be insured. Ihe best te*t of whether a title u\ninsurable, is to have it insured. Require a title Insurance policy\nwhen you buy.\nVALLEY ABSTRACT COMPANY\nPrompt Title Service\nBrownsville Edinburg\nOpposite Court House E. Ilarriman Fled.\nPhone 1184 Phone 93\n______________________________________________________","height":"36168","width":"27220"}}
